title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger 357 Mag SS
postcontent:
For Sale or Trade: This is a highly collectable Ruger Security Six 2 3/4" barrel 357 Magnum in Stainless Steel. This gun is in 99% condition, I say 99% as it is used but not much!!! No rust, scratches, or any other issues. It is flawless.

When I say highly collectable, first off it was made in 1975, this was the first year Ruger made this gun in Stainless Steel, also this is a PRE-WARNING revolver. In 1977 Ruger started put warning stamps on the barrel stating to read owners manuel etc... before using the gun. My gun has no warning, lastly it is the snub nose version made with a 2 3/4" barrel, these are alot harder to come by as the production numbers on these length barrels were very limited. It has adjustable sights as well. Try and find a 2 3/4" Pre warning in this condition, you wont, I searched two years before I found this one and it was a fluke, they are just not out there for sale very often???

I have a nice pair of Hogue Grips on the gun and I also have the original wooden grips, the original grips are mint condition. This gun has been fired very little and lockup is super tight and the trigger in single action is crisp, so crisp and light it is amazing. One of the best pistols I have ever owned and fired. Selling it to fund another project!

Lastly this gun comes with a handmade leather holster, this holster was special made for this gun and the two combine for a excellent carry piece.
This gun also comes with two Dade speed loaders and some ammo.

I will accept reasonable offers on this gun package. Additional pictures available upon request. Wichita area only FTF

title: For Sale:  Armslist.com for dummies
postcontent:
A face-to-face private party sale of a firearm using Armslist.com adds value to some people (convenience, speed, ability to trade, etc.).  Other methods of obtaining a firearm can involve sales tax, reams of paperwork, shipping charges, FFL transfer fees, travel, etc.

There’s a fool born every day who will pay more for something than it’s worth.  If you’re a slick salesman and can get more – good for you.  There are opportunistic people out there who would love to take advantage of someone experiencing financial difficulty, but let’s not talk about the mortgage industry now.

A new gun is worth more than the same used gun when all else is equal.  Used firearms, like used cars, can have mechanical problems.  You can sell your mechanical problems to someone else, and there is no law that says you have to disclose the problem.  Let the buyer beware.

Fair market value is about supply and demand.  “Market” is the price someone can and will spend to obtain a comparable gun.  Abundance will drive the price down and scarcity will drive the price up. 

If you and I have comparable guns for sale/trade in the same geographic area, and you’re asking $500 and I’m asking $400, it doesn’t really matter how pretty you are.  My gun is the better value in the eyes of a buyer.  On the other hand, if my price is higher, then maybe my wife politely suggested that I “SELL SOME OF THOSE DAMN GUNS” and placing this ad gets her off my case without really risking my guns.  

Nobody likes finding out they paid too much for something.  When you list a gun at close to what you paid for it, and people point out that there are cheaper prices elsewhere for comparable guns, they are NOT putting you down.  They’re interested in your gun, or they wouldn’t have looked.  They’re weighing all the factors between getting the gun from you and getting it elsewhere.  Maybe if your asking price was little closer to market, they’d buy it.  It's called negotiating.
